<div id='communityQuestionsWithAnswers'>
<div class='communityQuestionAndAnswer'>
<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
<a class="spoiler" href="/questions/1226931-i-guess-i-am-not-very-bright-i-did-not">This question contains spoilers...</a>
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[I guess I am not very bright. I did not understand how the story ended. Did they kill the priest and the jefe just went home to his wife and child? <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_1226931'><a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F3690.The_Power_and_the_Glory">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/1226931-i-guess-i-am-not-very-bright-i-did-not">3 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/1226931-i-guess-i-am-not-very-bright-i-did-not">See all 2 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/45526316-heather-keimig"><img alt="" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_100x100-259587f1619f5253426a4fa6fb508831.png" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/45526316-heather-keimig">Heather Keimig</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
This answer contains spoilers…
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[
  
    Yes, the priest we followed through the story was shot in the end (we are told of him crumpling up at the execution range, etc.). However, a new pries<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">…more</a>
    Yes, the priest we followed through the story was shot in the end (we are told of him crumpling up at the execution range, etc.). However, a new priest then shows up at the *very* end of the story, to be taken in by the family we have met several times through the story (the pious woman who reads the tales of martyrdom to her children; her daughters seem to be inclined to piety; her son is disinterested and unmoved). The most significant change happens in that son, who suddenly connects the dots, so to speak, between the stories his mother has read to him, the priest (who they had sheltered at some point before the story begins) who he now witnesses being killed (watching through the window or something) and the new priest walking in the door at the very end. Something galvanizes in him to oppose the military leaders he sees in his world (the lieutenant and the jefe) and he shifts from being interested in the lieutenant's weapons, to spitting at him through the window of his home.<br />I don't recall any family mentioned for the lieutenant and, frankly, didn't pay a whole lot of attention to the jefe, other than to see that he was continually portrayed as very shallow and frivolous with the terrific power he has at his disposal.<br />By the way, I don't think you "aren't very bright" for asking that question. One of the more interesting literary devices that Greene used in this book was to not name anyone! It speaks to the "everyman"-ness of the ways the characters thought/acted, but it also sets up the way that he then ends the story - the murder of the one priest and the arrival of his replacement, so to speak. Catholic priests wear vestments during the Mass for several reasons, one of the chief ones is to help you see "priest" not "man" (like a particular man, who dresses a certain way, wears a certain watch, and so forth). It is to help you see the Mass and not the dude. : )<br />The story was written the same way. We see the thoughts, the actions, the beliefs, the intense struggles, the failings, the successes - but not the names. Masterful! (But it does add a layer of "who's on first" to the reading of it, until you get the hang of it! LOL!)<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">(less)</a>
  
 <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
</div>
</span>
</div>
</div>
